# yolo-live Git Workflow (MANDATORY)

This project uses a strict develop-branch + feature-branch workflow. Follow it for every feature, fix, or non-trivial change without being reminded.

## Branching model

- `main` is the stable release branch. **Never** commit directly to `main`.
- `develop` is the integration branch. **Never** commit directly to `develop` from an agent session.
- Every new piece of work happens on a dedicated **feature branch** cut from `develop`.
- Feature branch naming: `feature/<short-kebab-case-description>`.
  - Examples: `feature/voice-hotkey`, `feature/memory-rag`, `feature/reasoning-tokens`, `fix/input-focus`.

## Start-of-task protocol

Before writing any code for a new feature:

1. Run `git status` to confirm the working tree is clean. If it isn't, stop and ask the user how to handle uncommitted work.
2. `git checkout develop && git pull` to make sure we're current.
3. `git checkout -b feature/<name>` — create the feature branch.
4. Only then begin the work.

If the user starts describing a new feature and we're not already on a feature branch for it, create one first. Do not silently pile new work onto an existing feature branch that's about a different thing.

## During the task

- Commit in logical chunks. Each commit message should explain the *why* in 1–2 sentences, not just the *what*.
- Push the feature branch to `origin` as soon as the first real commit lands (`git push -u origin feature/<name>`), so work is never only on the local machine.
- Never force-push a shared branch without explicit user permission.

## PMC — Push, Merge, Close

When the user says the feature is good, or says "pmc", execute this sequence in order, without prompting unless a step fails:

```bash
# 1. PUSH — make sure the feature branch is fully up on origin
git push

# 2. MERGE — fast-forward develop with the feature branch
git checkout develop
git pull
git merge --no-ff feature/<name> -m "Merge feature/<name> into develop"
git push

# 3. CLOSE — delete the feature branch locally and on origin
git branch -d feature/<name>
git push origin --delete feature/<name>

# Leave the working tree on develop, clean, current.
git status
```

Use `--no-ff` on the merge so the feature's history is preserved as a visible branch in the graph.

## Releasing to main

`main` **only moves when `develop` has been pushed and has absorbed the change first.** Never merge a feature branch into `main` directly, never cherry-pick a feature commit onto `main`, and never push to `main` ahead of `develop`.

The release flow is always:

```bash
# Preconditions: feature work is already merged into develop AND pushed.
git checkout develop && git pull
# Confirm origin/develop contains what we want on main. If it doesn't, stop.

git checkout main && git pull
git merge --no-ff develop -m "Release: merge develop into main"
git push
git checkout develop   # leave the working tree back on develop
```

If `origin/develop` isn't ahead of `origin/main`, there is nothing to release — do not invent a release. `main` is only ever a subset of what's already on `develop`.

## Hard rules

- **Never** commit or push to `main` or `develop` from a feature context.
- **Never** start work without a feature branch.
- **Never** delete a feature branch until the merge is confirmed on `origin/develop`.
- **Never** skip `git pull` before branching off `develop` or merging into it.
- **Never** use `git commit --no-verify` or `git push --force` unless the user explicitly asks for it.
- **Never** push `main` ahead of `develop`. `main` must always be a merge target *from* `develop`, never a shortcut around it.

## Quick reference

| User says… | You do… |
| --- | --- |
| "Let's build X" | Create `feature/<x>` from latest `develop`, start work |
| "This looks good" / "pmc" | Run the PMC sequence above |
| "Release this" | Merge `develop` into `main`, push both |
| "Abandon this" | `git checkout develop && git branch -D feature/<name> && git push origin --delete feature/<name>` (after confirming with user) |
